module AxiomSafe

(* THE CONTROL for the fourth false proof, and the file where the ONE axiom V1 has
   about an uninterpreted symbol is doing all the work.

   `string_length` is opaque: the logic cannot compute it, and congruence alone rules
   out nothing — as far as entailment is concerned a string could have length -10, and
   then `string_length(s) + 4` could be negative and dividing by it would be a bug.
   The obligation is discharged by `refine.NONNEG_UF`, instantiated at the one term
   this program mentions: `string_length(s) >= 0`, so the divisor is at least 4.

   The mutant is this file plus one declaration. Keep them side by side: the axiom is
   true of the PRIMITIVE, and the primitive is what this program calls.

   Checked, and then RUN: string_length("abc") is 3, so it prints 100 / 7 = 14. *)

fn div(a : Int, b : {v : Int | v > 0}) : Int = a / b

fn safe(s : String) : Int = div(100, string_length(s) + 4)

fn main(io : IO) : IO = print(io, show(safe("abc")))
